<doc id="450515" wikidata="Q2410467" url="?curid=450515" title="Azuma's inequality">
<text>In probability theory, the Azuma–Hoeffding inequality (named after Kazuoki Azuma and Wassily Hoeffding) gives a concentration result for the values of martingales that have bounded differences.

Suppose formula_1 is a martingale (or super-martingale) and

:formula_2

almost surely. Then for all positive integers &quot;N&quot; and all positive reals &quot;formula_3&quot;,

:formula_4

And symmetrically (when &quot;X&quot;&quot;k&quot; is a sub-martingale):

:formula_5

If &quot;X&quot; is a martingale, using both inequalities above and applying the union bound allows one to obtain a two-sided bound:

:formula_6

==Proof==
The proof shares similar idea of the proof for the general form of Azuma&#x27;s inequality listed below. Actually, this can be viewed as a direct corollary of the general form of Azuma&#x27;s inequality.

==A general form of Azuma&#x27;s inequality==

===Limitation of the vanilla Azuma&#x27;s inequality===
Note that the vanilla Azuma&#x27;s inequality requires symmetric bounds on martingale increments, i.e. formula_7. So, if known bound is asymmetric, e.g. formula_8, to use Azuma&#x27;s inequality, one need to choose formula_9 which might be a waste of information on the boundedness of formula_10. However, this issue can be resolved and one can obtain a tighter probability bound with the following general form of Azuma&#x27;s inequality.

===Statement===
Let formula_11 be a martingale (or supermartingale) with respect to filtration formula_12. Assume there are predictable processes formula_13 and formula_14 with respect to formula_15, i.e. for all formula_16, formula_17 are formula_18-measurable, and constants formula_19 such that
:formula_20
almost surely. Then for all formula_21,
:formula_22
Since a submartingale is a supermartingale with signs reversed, we have if instead formula_23 is a martingale (or submartingale),
:formula_24
If formula_23 is a martingale, since it is both a supermartingale and submartingale, by applying union bound to the two inequalities above, we could obtain the two-sided bound:
:formula_26

===Proof===
We will prove the supermartingale case only as the rest are self-evident. By Doob decomposition, we could decompose supermartingale formula_27 as formula_28 where formula_29 is a martingale and formula_30 is a nonincreasing predictable sequence (Note that if formula_27 itself is a martingale, then formula_32). From formula_33, we have
