<doc id="450525" wikidata="Q915079" url="?curid=450525" title="Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm">
<text>In cryptography, the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) offers a variant of the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA) which uses elliptic-curve cryptography.

==Key and signature sizes==
As with elliptic-curve cryptography in general, the bit size of the private key believed to be needed for ECDSA is about twice the size of the security level, in bits. For example, at a security level of 80 bits—meaning an attacker requires a maximum of about formula_1 operations to find the private key—the size of an ECDSA private key would be 160 bits. On the other hand, the signature size is the same for both DSA and ECDSA: approximately formula_2 bits, where formula_3 is the exponent in the formula formula_4, that is, about 320 bits for a security level of 80 bits, which is equivalent to formula_1 operations.

==Signature generation algorithm==
Suppose Alice wants to send a signed message to Bob. Initially, they must agree on the curve parameters formula_6. In addition to the field and equation of the curve, we need formula_7, a base point of prime order on the curve; formula_8 is the multiplicative order of the point formula_7.

The order formula_8 of the base point formula_7 must be prime. Indeed, we assume that every nonzero element of the ring formula_12 is invertible, so that formula_12 must be a field. It implies that formula_8 must be prime (cf. Bézout&#x27;s identity).

Alice creates a key pair, consisting of a private key integer formula_15, randomly selected in the interval formula_16; and a public key curve point formula_17. We use formula_18 to denote elliptic curve point multiplication by a scalar.

For Alice to sign a message formula_19, she follows these steps:

# Calculate formula_20. (Here HASH is a cryptographic hash function, such as SHA-2, with the output converted to an integer.)
# Let formula_21 be the formula_22 leftmost bits of formula_23, where formula_22 is the bit length of the group order formula_8. (Note that formula_21 can be &quot;greater&quot; than formula_8 but not &quot;longer&quot;.)
# Select a cryptographically secure random integer formula_28 from formula_16.
# Calculate the curve point formula_30.
# Calculate formula_31. If formula_32, go back to step 3.
# Calculate formula_33. If formula_34, go back to step 3.
# The signature is the pair formula_35. (And formula_36 is also a valid signature.)

As the standard notes, it is not only required for formula_28 to be secret, but it is also crucial to select different formula_28 for different signatures. Otherwise, the equation in step 6 can be solved for formula_15, the private key: given two signatures formula_35 and formula_41, employing the same unknown formula_28 for different known messages formula_19 and formula_44, an attacker can calculate formula_21 and formula_46, and since formula_47 (all operations in this paragraph are done modulo formula_8) the attacker can find formula_49. Since formula_50, the attacker can now calculate the private key formula_51. 

This implementation failure was used, for example, to extract the signing key used for the PlayStation 3 gaming-console. 

Another way ECDSA signature may leak private keys is when formula_28 is generated by a faulty random number generator. Such a failure in random number generation caused users of Android Bitcoin Wallet to lose their funds in August 2013. 

To ensure that formula_28 is unique for each message, one may bypass random number generation completely and generate deterministic signatures by deriving formula_28 from both the message and the private key.

==Signature verification algorithm==
For Bob to authenticate Alice&#x27;s signature formula_55 on a message formula_19, he must have a copy of her public-key curve point formula_57. Bob can verify formula_57 is a valid curve point as follows:

# Check that formula_57 is not equal to the identity element , and its coordinates are otherwise valid.
# Check that formula_57 lies on the curve.
# Check that formula_61.

After that, Bob follows these steps:

# Verify that and are integers in formula_16. If not, the signature is invalid.
# Calculate formula_20, where HASH is the same function used in the signature generation. 
# Let formula_21 be the formula_22 leftmost bits of .
# Calculate formula_66 and formula_67.
# Calculate the curve point formula_68. If formula_69 then the signature is invalid.
# The signature is valid if formula_70, invalid otherwise.

Note that an efficient implementation would compute inverse formula_71 only once. Also, using Shamir&#x27;s trick, a sum of two scalar multiplications formula_72 can be calculated faster than two scalar multiplications done independently.

===Correctness of the algorithm===
It is not immediately obvious why verification even functions correctly. To see why, denote as the curve point computed in step 5 of verification,

