<doc id="450536" wikidata="Q1465057" url="?curid=450536" title="Schnorr signature">
<text>In cryptography, a Schnorr signature is a digital signature produced by the Schnorr signature algorithm that was described by Claus Schnorr. It is a digital signature scheme known for its simplicity, among the first whose security is based on the intractability of certain discrete logarithm problems. It is efficient and generates short signatures. It was covered by which expired in February 2010.

==Algorithm==

===Choosing parameters===
*All users of the signature scheme agree on a group formula_1 of prime order formula_2 with generator formula_3 in which the discrete log problem is assumed to be hard. Typically a Schnorr group is used.
*All users agree on a cryptographic hash function formula_4.

===Notation===
In the following,
*Exponentiation stands for repeated application of the group operation
*Juxtaposition stands for multiplication on the set of congruence classes or application of the group operation (as applicable)
*Subtraction stands for subtraction on the set of congruence classes
*formula_5, the set of finite bit strings
*formula_6, the set of congruence classes modulo formula_2
*formula_8.

===Key generation===
*Choose a private signing key formula_9 from the allowed set.
*The public verification key is formula_10.

===Signing===
To sign a message formula_11:
*Choose a random formula_12 from the allowed set.
*Let formula_13.
*Let formula_14, where formula_15 denotes concatenation and formula_16 is represented as a bit string.
*Let formula_17.

The signature is the pair, formula_18.

Note that formula_19; if formula_20, then the signature representation can fit into 64 bytes.

===Verifying===
*Let formula_21
*Let formula_22

If formula_23 then the signature is verified.

===Proof of correctness===
It is relatively easy to see that formula_23 if the signed message equals the verified message:

formula_25, and hence formula_26.

Public elements: formula_1, formula_3, formula_2, formula_30, formula_31, formula_32, formula_16. Private elements: formula_12, formula_9.

This shows only that a correctly signed message will verify correctly; many other properties are required for a secure signature algorithm.

===Key leakage from nonce reuse===

Just as with the closely related signature algorithms DSA, ECDSA, and ElGamal, reusing the secret nonce value formula_12 on two Schnorr signatures of different messages will allow observers to recover the private key. In the case of Schnorr signatures, this simply requires subtracting formula_31 values:

: formula_38.

If formula_39 but formula_40 then formula_9 can be simply isolated. In fact, even slight biases in the value formula_12 or partial leakage of formula_12 can reveal the private key, after collecting sufficiently many signatures and solving the hidden number problem.

===Security argument===
The signature scheme was constructed by applying the Fiat–Shamir transformation to Schnorr&#x27;s identification protocol. Therefore, (as per Fiat and Shamir&#x27;s arguments), it is secure if formula_44 is modeled as a random oracle.

Its security can also be argued in the generic group model, under the assumption that formula_44 is &quot;random-prefix preimage resistant&quot; and &quot;random-prefix second-preimage resistant&quot;. In particular, formula_44 does &quot;not&quot; need to be collision resistant.

In 2012, Seurin provided an exact proof of the Schnorr signature scheme. In particular, Seurin shows that the security proof using the forking lemma is the best possible result for any signature schemes based on one-way group homomorphisms including Schnorr-type signatures and the Guillou–Quisquater signature schemes. Namely, under the ROMDL assumption, any algebraic reduction must lose a factor formula_47 in its time-to-success ratio, where formula_48 is a function that remains close to 1 as long as &quot;formula_49 is noticeably smaller than 1&quot;, where formula_49 is the probability of forging an error making at most formula_51 queries to the random oracle.

==Short Schnorr signatures==

The aforementioned process achieves a &quot;t&quot;-bit security level with 4&quot;t&quot;-bit signatures. For example, a 128-bit security level would require 512-bit (64-byte) signatures. The security is limited by discrete logarithm attacks on the group, which have a complexity of the &quot;square-root&quot; of the group size.

In Schnorr&#x27;s original 1991 paper, it was suggested that since collision resistance in the hash is not required, shorter hash functions may be just as secure, and indeed recent developments suggest that a &quot;t&quot;-bit security level can be achieved with 3&quot;t&quot;-bit signatures. Then, a 128-bit security level would require only 384-bit (48-byte) signatures, and this could be achieved by truncating the size of &quot;e&quot; until it is half the length of the &quot;s&quot; bitfield.

== Implementations ==
Schnorr signature is used by numerous products. A notable usage is the deterministic Schnorr&#x27;s signature using the secp256k1 elliptic curve for Bitcoin transaction signature after the Taproot update.

==See also==
* DSA
* EdDSA
* ElGamal signature scheme

